Here's how to implement all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs`** — intercept back navigation and cancel it if the user wants to stay:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only guard back (Pop) navigation from EditProductPage
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
            .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                           "Discard your changes?",
                           "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key point: `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation dialog is async. Without it you'd have a race condition.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — add this in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard above fires automatically
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

The `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the default back arrow with the word "Cancel". The `Command` routes the tap through `GoToAsync("..")`, which triggers the same `OnNavigating` guard—so both the hardware/swipe back and the button are protected.
